President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate Willie L. Phillips, Jr. as a Commissioner of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC). FERC is an independent agency that regulates the transmission of natural gas, oil, electricity, and other energy projects. Its role is to ensure that consumers have access to affordable, efficient, safe, reliable, and secure energy services. As part of the Biden Administration's efforts to address the climate crisis and create a clean electricity grid by 2035, FERC will play a crucial role in regulating the transmission of carbon-free energy across the country.

Willie L. Phillips, Jr. is an experienced regulatory attorney with almost 20 years of legal expertise in utility regulation, private practice, and as in-house counsel. He has a strong background in public utility regulation, bulk power system reliability, and corporate governance. As Chairman of the Public Service Commission of the District of Columbia, Phillips led efforts to modernize the energy grid, implement clean energy and climate goals, and protect customers. He has also worked for the North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), a regulatory authority responsible for ensuring the security and reliability of the bulk power system. Phillips is an active member of the National Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners (NARUC) and holds a Juris Doctor from Howard University School of Law and a Bachelor of Science from the University of Montevallo.